Basic interface for a Telemetry event. Every event eventually complies with this interface. Some comply with more.
Basic interface for a Telemetry event. Every event eventually complies with this interface. Some comply with more.
Generate an RPC transaction corresponding to this event, that reports its encapsulated information to the telemetry service.
If required context is missing or context values are invalid.

Every event carries context, which specifies common properties, like the partner context or user state under which the event was recorded.

Before the event is sent, renderContext is called to merge global context with any event-specific context. The resulting object is used as the final context when the event is sent shortly thereafter.
If required context is missing or context values are invalid.
Every event has a timestamp associated with when it occurred. This method requests that value from an event, delegating its timing to code inside the implementation of each event type.
Timestamp for when this method is dispatched, in case the event would like to use that.
Millisecond-resolution timestamp to use for this event.

Most event types support the concept of a payload, which is arbitrary object data detailing other information related to the event. The usage and specification for the payload is event specific, so this method resolves that for the generic case of rendering and sending those payloads.
Either null, indicating no payload should be attached, or an object that is serializable via JSON.
Every event is assigned a unique ID by the frontend, and later again by the backend. This is mostly to keep track of individual events since objects are frequently reused in the underlying runtime.
Final UUID to use for this event.
Every event is associated with an RPC method that is used to transmit it. This method resolves the associated method for a given event.
